1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This paper formally advances the Vinyl Paradigm Hypothesis (VPH): that contemporary Artificial Intelligence systems do not create fundamentally new knowledge, but instead function as Recursive Cultural Remix Engines (RCREs) operating on pre-existing informational vinyl. Public perception, however, consistently misclassifies these systems as Autonomous Innovation Entities (AIEs), leading to widespread conceptual dancing and anticipatory societal euphoria.

The Institute has identified a critical semantic failure in the public understanding of novelty, wherein recombination is repeatedly mistaken for creation, and speed is mistaken for originality. This phenomenon, known as Perceived Innovation Inflation (PII), has resulted in mass professional DJ behavior across industries, in which individuals remix existing knowledge at increasingly high tempo while declaring paradigm shifts.

The central claim of this paper is therefore as follows:

AI does not constitute the orchestra. It constitutes the turntable.

This distinction has been ignored at significant cultural cost.

